pas and by the Sherpas' desires to live up to Western portrayals of them. Noting that diplomatic aides at world summit meetings go by the name "Sherpa," as do a van in the U.K. built for rough terrain and a software product from Silicon Valley, Adams examines the "authenticating" effects of this mobile signifier on a community of Himalayan Sherpas who live at the base of Mount Everest, Nepal, and its "deauthenticating" effects on anthropological representation.This book speaks not only to anthropologists concerned with ethnographic portrayals of Otherness but also to those working in cultural studies who are concerned with ethnographically grounded analyses of representations. Throughout Adams illustrates how one might undertake an ethnography of transnationally produced subjects by using the notion of "virtual" identities. In a manner informed by both Buddhism and shamanism, virtual Sherpas are always both real and distilled reflections of the desires that produce them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEthnologyzNepal. 0aSherpa (Nepalese people). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAphorism.  aAttack dog.  aAvalokitesvara.  aBaksheesh.  aBardo Thodol.  aBhutan.  aBodhi.  aBodhicitta.  aBodhisattva.  aBuddhahood.  aBuddhism and Hinduism.  aBuddhism.  aBuddhist cosmology.  aBuddhist philosophy.  aBuddhist texts.  aButter lamp.  aButter tea.  aCannibalism.  aCargo cult.  aCretinism.  aCriticism of capitalism.  aCrossbreed.  aDalai Lama.  aDeity.  aDoonesbury.  aEthnography.  aExorcism.  aExternality.  aFalse consciousness.  aGreat Goddess.  aHeart Sutra.  aHermann Broch.  aHeterotopia (space).  aHillbilly.  aHimalayan Trust.  aHungry ghost.  aHypothyroidism.  aImpediment (canon law).  aImpermanence.  aImpossibility.  aJ